","1018":"1018","1017":"1017","1014":"1014","before 1045":"before 1045","1045":"1045","0991":"0991","1032":"1032","1010":"1010","1095":"1095","1094":"1094","1093":"1093","1070":"1070","Morgannwg Gwlad, Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Coity, Glamorgan, Wales":"Coity, Glamorgan, Wales","Europe":"Europe","Wales":"Wales","Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Meurig","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Mauricius</i> via Old Welsh <i>Mouric</i>.  See  <b>Maurice</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Meuric","meanings":["From Latin <i>Mauricius</i> via Old Welsh <i>Mouric</i>.  See  <b>Maurice</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Gwrgan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Meath): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Geargáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Geargán</i>’ or shortened from <b>Mac Geargáin</b> ‘son of <i>Geargán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>garg</i> ‘fierce’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gwlad","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Gudrun, Sten.","English: from a short form of the various Old English personal names with the first element <i>glæd</i> ‘shining, joyful’. Compare   Gladwin  .","Scandinavian and English: nickname for a cheerful person, from Scandinavian, Middle English <i>glad</i> ‘merry’, ‘jolly’. Compare   Gladd   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Gladd","meanings":["Gad or gaed, a point of a weapon, a prick, a goad; also from gad, want, need, deficiency"]},{"name":"Gladman","meanings":["English (Sussex and Middlesex): from the Middle English personal name <i>Gladman</i>, Old English <i>Glædmann</i>. See   Glad  ."]},{"name":"Glatz","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic):","nickname for a bald man, from Middle High German <i>gla(t)z</i> ‘bald head, bald’ (a derivative of Middle High German, Old High German <i>glat</i> ‘smooth, shiny’, an equivalent of   Glad  ), German <i>Glatze</i> ‘baldness’. In some cases the German surname may be topographic for someone living on a bare, treeless hill.","habitational name from Glatz, the German name of Kłodzko in Lower Silesia, Poland."]},{"name":"Gladwin","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, itself from a medieval given name derived from Old English <i>glæd</i> ‘bright’ + <i>wine</i> ‘friend’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Meurig ap Gwrgan of Morgannwg Gwlad was born in 1017, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, King Gwrgan of Glywysing and Glamorgan, was 7 and his mother, Angharad Nest verch Gwyn of Powys, was 26. He married Gwerystan of Glamorgan before 1045, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1045, in Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1017–1045":"1017–1045","1014–1093":"1014–1093","1018–Female":"1018–Surnud","1094–Female":"1094–Surnud","1045–1095":"1045–1095","–Male":"Surnud","1010–1070":"1010–1070","0991–1032":"0991–1032","1018":"1018","1017":"1017","1014":"1014","before 1045":"enne 1045","1045":"1045","0991":"0991","1032":"1032","1010":"1010","1095":"1095","1094":"1094","1093":"1093","1070":"1070","Morgannwg Gwlad, Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Coity, Glamorgan, Wales":"Coity, Glamorgan, Wales","Europe":"Europe","Wales":"Wales","Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandeilo, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1017–1045":"1017–1045","1014–1093":"1014–1093","1018–Female":"1018–Kuollut","1094–Female":"1094–Kuollut","1045–1095":"1045–1095","